  <p>You light the fire, the room fills with smoke, and you're left opening windows in the middle of winter wondering what's gone wrong. Smoke coming back down the chimney — sometimes called backdraught or downdraught — is one of the most common problems we get called out to fix in Melbourne. The good news: in the vast majority of cases, the cause is identifiable and the fix is straightforward.</p>

  <p>Here's a complete rundown of why chimney smoke comes back down, how to diagnose which issue you're dealing with, and what to do about it.</p>

  <h2>Why Does Smoke Come Back Down the Chimney?</h2>

  <p>A chimney works by creating a column of hot, rising air that pulls combustion gases and smoke upward and out of the flue. When that upward airflow — called draw or draft — fails or reverses, smoke has nowhere to go except back into the room. The direction of airflow through the flue depends on a balance of temperature, pressure and physical clearance. Anything that disrupts that balance can cause smoke to come back down.</p>

  <h2>The Most Common Causes</h2>

  <h3>1. Blocked or Heavily Sooted Flue</h3>

  <p>This is the most common cause of smoke coming back down the chimney, by a significant margin. Creosote and soot accumulate on the flue walls after every fire. Over a season — or multiple seasons without cleaning — the buildup can reduce the internal diameter of the flue significantly. A 150mm flue choked with creosote might have an effective opening of 80mm or less. That restriction prevents hot gases from rising freely, and they spill back into the room instead.</p>

  <p>If your chimney used to draw well and has gradually gotten worse, or if it started performing poorly at the beginning of this winter after sitting unused all summer — a dirty flue is almost certainly the cause. This requires a professional clean to fix. There's no DIY workaround that addresses the actual buildup.</p>

  <h3>2. Bird Nest or Debris Blockage</h3>

  <p>Melbourne's spring and summer months are prime nesting season for starlings, sparrows and other birds. An unused flue is an attractive spot — sheltered, dry, and out of reach. A nest built over the warmer months can partially or completely block the flue opening at the top, or get lodged partway down. When you light the first fire of the season, the smoke hits the blockage and comes straight back down.</p>

  <p>Signs of a nest: scratching or chirping sounds from the flue during spring or summer, twigs or debris falling into the firebox, or sudden severe smoke spillage on the first fire of the season. Do not attempt to burn through a nest — the dry material ignites easily and can cause a chimney fire. Get it professionally cleared first.</p>

  <h3>3. Cold Flue Downdraught</h3>

  <p>This one catches people off guard. On a cold morning — or if the heater hasn't been used for several days — the air inside the flue can be colder and denser than the outside air. When that's the case, the natural tendency of the air in the flue is to fall downward, not rise. When you light the fire, you're pushing warm air upward against a column of cold air that wants to come down. Until the flue warms up enough to reverse that tendency, smoke comes back into the room.</p>

  <p>Cold flue downdraught is most common on very cold mornings, in heaters that haven't been used recently, and in flues that run on an outside wall where the flue pipe is exposed to cold air throughout. The fix is to prime the flue before lighting the main fire: roll up a piece of newspaper, light it, and hold it inside the firebox near the throat of the flue for 30–60 seconds. This warms the air at the base of the flue and helps establish the upward draft before you load the heater.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>If cold flue downdraught is a recurring problem — especially in outside-wall flues — an insulated flue liner helps significantly by keeping the flue warmer between fires and reducing the temperature difference that causes the downdraught.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>4. Negative Air Pressure Inside the House</h3>

  <p>Modern Melbourne homes are increasingly well sealed — double-glazed windows, draught-proofed doors, bathroom exhaust fans, rangehood extractors. A wood heater draws in air to feed combustion. In a tightly sealed house, that draw can create negative pressure inside, where the air pressure indoors is lower than outside. When the pressure differential is strong enough, outside air is forced down the chimney to equalise it — and it brings smoke with it.</p>

  <p>Test for negative pressure by cracking a nearby window 3–4cm while the fire is struggling. If the smoke immediately clears and the fire improves, negative air pressure is your cause. The proper solution is a dedicated air supply vent near the heater — not just cracking windows every time you light a fire. A chimney professional can advise on options for your specific setup.</p>

  <h3>5. Wind Effect and Downdraught from Nearby Structures</h3>

  <p>Wind can cause chimney smoke to come back down in a couple of ways. If the chimney pot sits too low relative to the roofline, peak of the roof, or nearby structures (a second storey extension, a tall tree, a neighbouring building), wind can create a high-pressure zone over the top of the chimney that forces air downward. This is particularly noticeable on windy days when the problem gets worse, and on calm days when it largely disappears.</p>

  <p>The fix for wind-related downdraught is usually a chimney cowl — a cover designed to deflect wind and maintain upward draft regardless of wind direction. Anti-downdraught cowls are effective for most wind-driven cases. A professional can advise on the right cowl for your flue type and configuration.</p>

  <h3>6. Flue Too Short or Undersized</h3>

  <p>For a chimney to draw properly, it needs adequate height above the roofline — typically at least 600mm above the highest point of the roof within a certain radius. A flue that's too short won't generate enough thermal draft to pull smoke up reliably. Similarly, a flue diameter that's too small relative to the firebox opening won't handle the volume of smoke produced.</p>

  <p>These are structural issues rather than maintenance problems. They're less common than the causes above — particularly in homes where the heater has worked fine in the past — but do occur in older Melbourne properties where original chimneys have been shortened, modified, or incorrectly rebuilt over the decades.</p>

  <h3>7. Closed or Partially Closed Damper</h3>

  <p>Many older open fireplaces and some wood heaters have a damper — a metal plate that controls airflow through the flue. If the damper has been left closed or partially closed from the previous season, the flue is effectively blocked. The fix is simple: open the damper fully before lighting. On older systems the damper mechanism can corrode or seize, which requires repair or replacement.</p>

