  <h2>How to Stop Smoke Coming Back Down the Chimney — Step by Step</h2>

  <p>Work through these in order before calling a professional. Most cases are solved in the first two or three steps.</p>

  <p><strong>Check the damper first.</strong> If your fireplace has one, make sure it's fully open. It sounds obvious, but a surprising number of callouts are resolved at this step.</p>

  <p><strong>Prime the flue before lighting.</strong> On cold mornings, or if the heater hasn't been used for a while, warm the flue with a lit rolled newspaper held near the throat for 30–60 seconds before loading and lighting the main fire. Wait until you feel the draw establish — the warm air being pulled upward — then light the fire.</p>

  <p><strong>Test for negative air pressure.</strong> Crack a nearby window slightly while the fire is struggling. If draw immediately improves, the house is too airtight for the heater. Keep a small window cracked while the fire establishes, and consider a permanent air supply solution.</p>

  <p><strong>Check for a nest or blockage.</strong> If you can see or hear signs of a bird nest, or if the problem appeared suddenly at the start of the season, don't continue lighting fires. Get a professional inspection and clearance before using the heater.</p>

  <p><strong>Book a professional clean.</strong> If none of the above applies — or if the problem persists after checking all of the above — a blocked or sooted flue is almost certainly the cause. A professional clean clears the restriction, restores proper draft, and stops the smoke coming back in. In most cases, the difference is immediate and noticeable from the very first fire after the clean.</p>

  <h2>Is It a Safety Issue?</h2>

  <p>Yes — smoke coming back down the chimney isn't just a comfort problem. Smoke contains carbon monoxide (CO), particulates and other combustion gases. Sustained exposure in a closed room is a health risk. If you're repeatedly getting smoke spillage and the room is filling with smoke, don't keep lighting fires and hoping for the best — get the cause identified and fixed.</p>

  <p>A carbon monoxide detector in the room with the heater is essential if you don't already have one. CO is colourless and odourless and won't be detected without a detector even if it's reaching dangerous concentrations. A partial flue blockage can allow CO to accumulate without any visible smoke.</p>

  <h2>When to Call a Professional</h2>

  <p>If you've worked through the checklist above — confirmed the damper is open, primed the flue, ruled out negative pressure, and there's no obvious nest — and smoke is still coming back down the chimney, it's time for a professional clean and inspection. In Melbourne, a full clean for a flue and wood heater takes around 45–75 minutes, covers the entire flue from firebox to cap, and includes a condition report. For masonry or brick chimneys, allow up to 90 minutes.</p>

  <p>If the inspection reveals a structural issue — flue too short, damaged liner, incorrect sizing — that will be flagged as part of the report and you can weigh up your options from there. But in the majority of cases, it won't come to that. Creosote and soot buildup is the cause, a clean fixes it, and the problem doesn't come back until the buildup accumulates again — usually a year or more later with normal use and good firewood.</p>
